    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Bank, Southampton,</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>— 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> <hi rend="print">18</hi>80</date>
                    <salute>My dear Father,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I telegraphed to you to say that I had asked W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> James to call on you at Q. A. St.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> He sails for America on Wednesday; it is cruel to worry you directly you get home, but in case he did not see you, and you are fairly well and have a boy at home,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> could you ask him down to lunch or sleep on Sunday or Monday? He is very modest about going, but is very anxious to do so and is extremely pleasant.</p>
<p>His address is</p>
<p>3 Bolton Street</p>
<p>Piccadilly</p>
                    <p>I am very sorry I cannot come to meet him, if you do ask him let me know when in case I possibly could come.</p>
                    <p>I am very glad you had so pleasant a visit at Cambridge, and am sorry poor Mother was not quite brisk.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
                    <p>Sara<ref target="#foot.f4"/> comes tomorrow I am glad to say, I hope she saw you in London</p>
<p>Your affect son W. E. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2534.xml">William James</ref> had met <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref> in 1877 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11083.xml">E. Taylor 1990</ref>, p. 10). CD stayed at <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1211.xml">Erasmus Alvey Darwin</ref>’s house at 6 Queen Anne Street, London, from 19 to 21 August 1880 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">William probably meant one of CD’s other sons.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD and Emma were in Cambridge visiting <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1226.xml">Horace</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1227.xml">Ida Darwin</ref> from 14 to 19 August (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1240.xml">Sara Darwin</ref>.</note>
            
        </div>
    
